{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658111","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658111"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:46+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:41:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20707"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20707","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20707"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13583"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95803"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13583","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13583"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20707"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78582"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11585"},{"type":"tags","id":"11782"},{"type":"tags","id":"12585"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32648"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32650"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95803","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95803"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman presents with a non-healing ulcer on her lower leg that has been present for eight months. She has a history of varicose veins and congestive heart failure. On examination, the ulcer has irregular borders with surrounding brown-pigmented skin. The area is minimally painful.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiological mechanism underlying this patient\u0027s chronic wound?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tissue hypoxia due to venous hypertension","Bacterial biofilm formation preventing epithelialisation","Peripheral neuropathy causing repeated microtrauma","Excessive myofibroblast activity causing contracture","Systemic metabolic abnormalities impairing collagen synthesis"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has a venous leg ulcer, which is caused by \u003Cstrong\u003Etissue hypoxia due to venous hypertension\u003C/strong\u003E. The clinical features supporting this diagnosis include the presence of risk factors (varicose veins and congestive heart failure), the location on the lower leg, and the characteristic brown pigmentation surrounding the ulcer (haemosiderin deposition from red blood cell breakdown). Venous hypertension leads to poor oxygen delivery to the tissues, which impairs the normal wound healing process.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBacterial biofilm formation preventing epithelialisation\u003C/strong\u003E may contribute to wound chronicity but is not the primary underlying mechanism in venous ulcers.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeripheral neuropathy causing repeated microtrauma\u003C/strong\u003E is a mechanism more commonly associated with diabetic foot ulcers, where loss of sensation leads to unnoticed injuries and continued pressure on damaged tissue.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExcessive myofibroblast activity causing contracture\u003C/strong\u003E is associated with hypertrophic scars and keloids, which are forms of excessive scarring rather than chronic non-healing wounds.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESystemic metabolic abnormalities impairing collagen synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is more relevant to diabetic ulcers, where hyperglycaemia affects multiple aspects of wound healing including collagen production and remodelling.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVenous leg ulcers develop due to chronic venous hypertension causing increased hydrostatic pressure in the veins, leading to oedema, fibrin deposition around capillaries, and impaired oxygen and nutrient delivery to tissues. The resulting tissue hypoxia prevents normal healing processes from occurring effectively.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Chronic wounds fail to heal due to specific factors such as venous hypertension, arterial insufficiency, diabetes, or prolonged pressure.","Venous leg ulcers develop due to venous hypertension causing tissue hypoxia, fibrin cuffing, and impaired nutrient delivery.","Clinical features of venous ulcers include location on the lower leg, surrounding haemosiderin pigmentation, and association with varicose veins."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 3, Inflammation and Repair; p. 110-111"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78582"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20707"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78582","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78582"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T20:12:08+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T20:13:57+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13583"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95803"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11585","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11585"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Inflammation and repair","synonyms":[],"description":n